The Ever Given, a 220,940 ton container ship, is currently stuck in the Suez canal. The government of Egypt is losing hundreds of millions of dollars while global shipping has stalled. [[You are Klaus Kinski->suez]].The Suez Canal Authority has given you a staff of forty men, a budget of ten kilograms of gold, and an assortment of plate mail. You have been dead since German reunification and have an antisocial personality disorder. [[You must move the boat->methods]].You have three ideas. You can use the money to purchase thousands of pounds of military ordnance and attempt to [[blast the boat free of the canal->blast]]. You can tie ropes to the boat and recruit thousands more men to pull them with all of their might, in an act of enormous ingenuity and hubris [[in defiance of God->defy]]. You can phone your old friend [[Werner Herzog->werner]]. (set: $wernerprogress to 100) (set: $bomb to false)(if:$wernerprogress is 5)[(set: $wernerprogress to 4)You have five hours until Werner Herzog arrives. ]You explain to the canal authority that you are going to need as many explosives as possible. They seem understandably concerned, so you helpfully begin to explain the comprehensive knowledge of explosives that you gained during your time in the Luftwaffe during World War II. Rather than being impressed by your expertise, they now seem significantly more [[upset]].(if:$wernerprogress is 5)[(set: $wernerprogress to 4)You have five hours until Werner Herzog arrives. ]You need to recruit more men to your cause. You begin your recruitment efforts by explaining to your assembled men that, as they are, they are woefully inadequate, and cannot possibly hope to move a stuck boat on their own. You hope that this will inspire them to band together, to reach out to their fellow man, to make themselves more numerous. [[Instead they seem angry and start shouting->shouting]].You wave down a canal attendant and ask him to place a phone call for you. You remember the number for Werner Herzog's car phone. Werner Herzog loved his car phone. The canal attendant produces a tiny computer from his pocket. You immediately despise it and want to destroy it. He presses some buttons and hands it to you. [[You hear Werner Herzog's voice->returned]]."I kept this number for you, Klaus." [[That's good, Werner->killed]]."I always knew you would be back one day to torture me, Klaus." Yes, Werner. You were right. [[I cannot be killed->disappointed]]."I regretted that I was not able to kill you myself, Klaus." [[I too was disappointed, Werner->where]]."Where are you, Klaus?" I am in Egypt, Werner. I am helping the Egyptians with a boat. [[The boat has become defective->seeyou]]."I will see you in seven hours, Klaus." The line goes dead. (set: $wernerprogress to 7) [[Werner Herzog is on his way->enroute]].You have seven hours until Werner Herzog arrives. [[You can relax and take in the sun's warmth->relax]], here near the cradle of civilization, while considering all that has come to pass in human history up to this moment in which you, Klaus Kinski, have been revived from death in order to help maintain global supply chains. [[Or you can try another idea->meantime]] while you wait for Werner Herzog to arrive. (set: $wernerprogress to 6)Hello, Werner. "This is an extraordinary boat, Klaus." Yes, Werner. We must move it together. "Just a moment first, Klaus." [[He walks toward you->approach]].Werner Herzog does not stop walking until you are standing face to face. Not wanting to show fear, you refuse to move. "It is good to see you, Klaus." You cannot think of anything to say. You remember Werner's smell and are momentarily overcome. [[Werner Herzog embraces you->hug]].You have failed to move the boat. [[Try again->suez]].You have five hours until Werner Herzog arrives. It strikes you that you are not very good at relaxing. You decide to demonstrate your fortitude to yourself by [[swimming out into the middle of the canal->swim]]. (set: $wernerprogress to 4)You have six hours until Werner Herzog arrives. (if:$bomb is false)[You have two ideas. You can use the money to purchase thousands of pounds of military ordnance and attempt to [[blast the boat free of the canal->blast]]. You can tie ropes to the boat and recruit thousands more men to pull them with all of their might, in an act of enormous ingenuity and hubris [[in defiance of God->defy]].](if:$bomb is true)[You have one idea. You can tie ropes to the boat and recruit thousands more men to pull them with all of their might, in an act of enormous ingenuity and hubris [[in defiance of God->defy]].] (set: $wernerprogress to 5)(if:$wernerprogress is 4)[(set: $wernerprogress to 3)You have four hours until Werner Herzog arrives. ]Perhaps you have gone about this the wrong way. Perhaps you need to be kinder to the men. Perhaps they do not speak German. In any case, a new approach is needed. You need a champion, someone who can persuade them to tie enormous ropes to the enormous boat, and you suspect that not only have they not seen your films, it may not help if they had. [[You remember another film->otherfilm]].(if:$wernerprogress is 3)[(set: $wernerprogress to 2)You have three hours until Werner Herzog arrives. ]In this other film, a man who had clearly received a proper engineering education was nevertheless able to win the respect and trust of his filthy compatriots by showing them kindness and patience. This is it, this is perfect, this will work. Problem: this is not necessarily in our wheelhouse. We need to persuade the Egyptians to [[repeat their forbidden ritual->repeat]].(if:$wernerprogress is 2)[(set: $wernerprogress to 1)You have two hours until Werner Herzog arrives. ][[We need to resurrect Charlton Heston as Moses->Moses]].(if:$wernerprogress is 1)[(set: $wernerprogress to 0)You have one hour until Werner Herzog arrives. ]You explain this plan to the Egyptians and to your surprise they pretty much shrug and agree to go along with it. You worry that this reflects on their decision to bring you back to life and try not to think too hard about it, but it doesn't work, and you are now roiling with anguish. Mid-roil, the Egyptians explain to you that they have one condition for bringing back Charlton Heston: you must also bring back his Egyptian rival from the film, the pharaoh Rameses II, played by Yul Brynner. By this point you have become too angry to see or think clearly, but you don't want to risk having a big blowup in front of the Egyptians, so you quickly agree, and they [[get to work on conjuring the dead->ritual]].(if:$wernerprogress is 100)[You black out from fury for the duration of the ritual, retaining none of it, and when you come to, you are standing directly in front of Moses and Rameses, who appear to be in the middle of an intense flirtation. Male sexuality upsets you so you [[interrupt them immediately->interrupt]].](if:$wernerprogress is 0)[You black out from fury for the duration of the ritual, retaining none of it, and when you come to, you are standing directly in front of Moses, Rameses, and Werner Herzog. They are talking excitedly. [[Werner Herzog notices that you have woken up->movie]].]You explain to Moses that this is no time for homoeroticism, and that he's been brought back to life for a very important mission: he has to gather thousands more men, as well as some very large and strong ropes, for the important mission of pulling the big boat free from the shore. He understands you intuitively and dashes off to get to work. You are left alone with Ramesses. [[He stares coquettishly at you->coquette]].You have four hours until Werner Herzog arrives. You are floating on your back in the middle of the Suez Canal. [[You have led an interesting life->floating]]. (set: $wernerprogress to 3)You have three hours until Werner Herzog arrives. You hear a noise and look up to see a man on the shore angrily gesturing towards the boat and yelling at you. You decide to swim back over to the man to figure out what his problem is. Upon your arriving, he continues to shout, and begins furiously windmilling his arms. You punch the man in the throat and throw him into the Suez Canal. [[You wish Werner Herzog was here->throw]]. (set: $wernerprogress to 2)You have two hours until Werner Herzog arrives. You realize that you have not checked up on your men for some time. You wander around looking for them until you hear a faint commotion from the deck of the Ever Given. You look up at the boat and notice that a rope ladder is hanging from the starboard side, a little ways down from the front of the ship. [[You ascend the rope ladder->party]]. (set: $wernerprogress to 1)You have one hour until Werner Herzog arrives. At the top of the ladder, you find your forty men smoking and playing cards with the crew of the Ever Given. Your first instinct is to admonish them, but you slowly begin to realize that they are, in fact, engaged in a pure expression of human spirit, sharing this moment of kinship with one another, in spite of the incredible pressure on all of you to move the boat. You think to join in, but decide it would be inappropriate, and, smiling to yourself, [[quietly descend back down the ladder->time]]. [["Hello, Klaus"->helloklaus]]You let your arms fall limp at your sides. You cannot bear the tenderness he has shown you. "As I was saying, Klaus." You feel a tightness in your chest. You attribute this to your unusual emotional state. You are becoming lightheaded, which is something that normally only happens when you are very angry. You then notice that you are bleeding from your left side. [[Werner Herzog has stabbed you->death]]."Klaus," he begins, "I was coming here to kill you, but then I met these men, and they gave me an extraordinary idea. What if we were to attempt to remake The Ten Commandments film? I believe they tried to do it once in the nineties, but they made it into a children's film, which was not at all appropriate to the source material. This should be a film of blood and carnage, of conflict and triumph, and we must adapt it to the present day, so that the Moses figure can be tasked with moving this giant boat in order to impress Ramesses' father, emasculating Ramesses. I believe that if we bring the full resources of Hollywood to bear on the production of our film, then we may be able to make the greatest film of our time, and also move the boat." [[Werner Herzog has stolen your idea->stolen]].Fortunately, you ran down your supply of neurotransmitters during your last fit of rage, and so you elect not to start a fight with Werner Herzog. It is an excellent idea, you tell him, and you should begin production right away. You are not yet sure how they are going to incorporate your character into the film, but you are confident it will be a success. You give Moses and Ramesses a big thumbs-up. [[Your remake of The Ten Commandments enters production->production]].Several days into the construction of the film sets along the Ever Given, they begin slinging enormous ropes up and down the big boat. Movie extras from far and wide have come to join the cast. There must be over a million people present; you can hardly believe it. Everyone is invested in your success. (if:$bomb is true)[While walking the set and attempting to motivate the actors, you notice that the leak that you caused in the boat has started to worsen, and it appears to be sinking slightly deeper into the canal. Stirred by the forthrightness of the assembled masses, you decide that the time has come to admit to the botched demolition. You march off toward Werner Herzog's trailer, but find that he is busy in a meeting. However, his special director's chair is sitting unused outside of the trailer, and you've always wanted to sit in the chair. [[This will be a perfect way to celebrate a successful production->sit]].](if:$bomb is false)[You decide that it is time to motivate the actors to prepare for the climactic sequence of pulling the boat free of the Canal. You have not discussed this with anyone else involved in the production, but it feels like the right time, and you prefer to act on instinct. You walk up to the centermost rope, tie it around your waist, and scream at the top of your lungs. [[A crowd begins to gather->crowd]].]You are so excited to sit in the director's chair that you lurch forward at the last second and accidentally sit on your own balls, sending you into a fit of rage. Your destructive impulses engage and you begin to destroy the movie set in a berserk fury. Your memories at this point become hazy -- the last thing you remember is Werner Herzog emerging from his trailer with a stun gun, muttering "not again," and shooting you in the leg. [[You are unconscious for some time->unconscious]].You awake in a hospital room surrounded by balloons. As your vision comes gradually back into focus, you notice that the balloons say things on them like "Get Well Soon, Klaus!" and "Congratulations!" Suddenly, Moses and Ramesses burst into the room. "You're awake!" they shout in unison. "We could hardly believe it from the monitor! Werner shot you so many times that you went into a coma, and we were afraid you'd never wake up!" [[Good old Werner->debriefing]]."We moved the boat, thanks to you!" they explain. "The structural engineers took a look before we filmed the climactic sequence, and they noticed that you'd cleverly thought to drain most of the fuel from the stuck boat into the Suez Canal in order to make it lighter! We'd never have been able to pull it otherwise, but a million people came together to free it, and it was all because of your quick thinking, Klaus!" You are astonished. They go on to explain that Werner Herzog is currently directing a followup documentary about the cleanup of the fuel spill from the Suez Canal. It is attracting attention from environmental groups and should be very successful in its own right. continue screaming and gesticulating wildly at the boat. While you have still not answered the question of whether any of the assembled actors speak your language -- you wonder about this -- they appear to get the message. Everyone hurries to pick up the other ropes, and you are overwhelmed by the sheer scale of their coordination. You are a leader of millions, all gathered together to complete your majestic vision. You raise your hand with three fingers outstretched, and look behind you to see a massive wave of people echoing your movements. You lower one finger and then another, now looking straight ahead, gathering all of your strength in your core, ready to pull. Time slows down around you. [[You yank on the rope with all of your might->wait]].You are catapulted into the air like Wile E Coyote. You can hear Werner Herzog yell "Wait!" as you are flung directly at the boat's mast. As it turns out, most of the ropes had not yet been attached properly, so the extras' efforts primarily resulted in launching you upwards at breakneck speed. Your body makes a little "gong" noise as it bounces off of the Ever Given. [[You do not hear it->death]]."We must prepare to do battle," he explains. You aren't sure what to make of any of this. He proceeds to strip completely naked, removing his sash and tunic, then produces from behind him a vial of olive oil, which he empties directly over his perfectly bald head. It runs down every inch of his nude body. [[You frantically shake your head->nonono]]."Now!" shouts Ramesses, his voice sharp and hot. "En garde!" You cannot stop looking at his dick. This is a nightmare. He's coming right towards you. "Hiiii-ya!" he cries out, [[raising his blade->death]].(if:$wernerprogress is 4)[(set: $wernerprogress to 3)You have four hours until Werner Herzog arrives. ]Realizing your error, you explain that you were captured by the British on your second day of combat, and, upon hearing that prisoners of war were more likely to be returned home if they were desperately ill, cleverly decided to eat as many cigarettes as possible while captive, but unfortunately remained healthy as a horse, and were therefore innocent of any war crimes. The gentleman to whom you are speaking looks increasingly concerned and begins reaching for his handcuffs. You don't want to squander your big chance so soon, so you punch him in the throat, shut him in a locker, and resolve to [[buy your own explosives->explosives]].(if:$wernerprogress is 3)[(set: $wernerprogress to 2)You have three hours until Werner Herzog arrives. ]You gather your forty men and explain that they are to take your gold and use it to purchase as many bombs as possible. You are engaged for some time in a lecture on the various shapes and sizes of armaments, how best to disable an enemy vessel or open a passage through the jungle, etc., when you realize that most of them have left. [[Your intense focus as an actor is very impressive, even to you->focus]].(if:$wernerprogress is 2)[(set: $wernerprogress to 1)You have two hours until Werner Herzog arrives. ]Three of the men eventually return with a few sticks of dynamite and what looks like a homemade pipe bomb. You are profoundly disappointed and decide to take out your frustration with the deserters on the men who happened to have returned, berating them at length and at times violently. Eventually, you decide to make your remaining three men stand in a very rudimentary human pyramid whilst holding the dynamite and the pipe bomb, in the hopes that they can "get some good oxygen going with the elevation" and create a large enough explosion to compensate for their tiny payload. Just then, a fourth man [[returns with a wagonfull of semtex->semtex]].(if:$wernerprogress is 1)[(set: $wernerprogress to 0)You have one hour until Werner Herzog arrives. ]You are extremely pleased and promote the man to Lance Corporal on the spot. He seems proud. You order your men to wheel the wagon full of semtex over to the spot in front of the boat that appears, roughly, to be the most beached. You consider taking the semtex out of the wagon, but as you've had some trouble with waterproofing in the past, you decide it's safest to just detonate it as-is. Nobly, you then order them to stand back. You don the entire set of plate mail, light a stick of dynamite, drop it into the wagon, and prepare to [[run away as fast as you can->run]].(if:$wernerprogress is 100)[You make it a few paces before being blown clear. Incredibly, the plate mail absorbs most of the impact, and although it takes you a few minutes to stand up, your men seem amazed that you are alive. Beaming, you turn and look back towards the big boat. It remains lodged firmly into the bank of the canal but now has a hole in it about a meter wide. After an exaggerated delay, a liquid begins to trickle out of the hole at a rate very much like that of urine. This is pretty pitiful, and, not wanting anyone else to find out, you take off the plate mail and try to cram it all into the hole. To your surprise it mostly fits into the shape's diameter, and it is very narrowly possible that someone would not be able to notice the hole from a distance. (set: $bomb to true)You now have two ideas. You can tie ropes to the boat and recruit thousands more men to pull them with all of their might, in an act of enormous ingenuity and hubris [[in defiance of God->defy]]. You can phone your old friend [[Werner Herzog->werner]].](if:$wernerprogress is 0)[Just as you turn to run, you see your old friend Werner Herzog approaching from a distance. He seems to suss out the situation pretty quickly, as he is also carrying a semtex detonator, which is not something that had occurred to you would be useful. He gives you an exaggerated salute, around which time you realize that you've forgotten to start running. [[You are more or less vaporized->death]].]
